post_text: During the past two weeks, Joanie Siler, an independent beauty consultant with Mary Kay and a Caesar Rodney High School Alumni, presented the entire custodial staff at Caesar Rodney School District with Mary Kay’s Satin Hands Repair Kit, which was part of Mary Kay’s Hometown Heroes Project. Joanie, who lives in the Camden area, and is passionate about the Caesar Rodney School District, received a very large donation from the Class of 1980 reunion committee. The donation was matched by a classmate from the Class of 1985 and followed with additional donations. With the money, Joanie started by giving Mary Kay Satin Hands Repair Kits to the child nutrition staff who have been feeding the community. Joanie then gave Satin Hands Repair Kits to the front office staff at Caesar Rodney High School. “I do appreciate you and I wanted you to know that the community does also,” said Joanie Siler. #cr #goriders #netde #edude #marykay

post_text:
Caesar Rodney School District to Launch an Instructional Support Hotline

The Caesar Rodney School District is launching an instructional support hotline on Tuesday, May 12, 2020 that will be available for parents who would like support in helping their child with ELA, Math, Science, and Social Studies content. Staff will be available from 9:00am - 5:00pm on Tuesdays and Wednesdays.

If you need support for ELA, Math, Science, or Social Studies, please call (302) 943-7572.

In addition, if your child attends one of our countywide schools, please call the following hotline number (302) 943-0829.

When calling, please leave both your name, your child’s name and grade, a phone number you can be reached at, and a brief description of what you need support with so we can ensure the right person is able to provide you with the necessary information.
text:
Caesar Rodney School District to Launch an Instructional Support Hotline

The Caesar Rodney School District is launching an instructional support hotline on Tuesday, May 12, 2020 that will be available for parents who would like support in helping their child with ELA, Math, Science, and Social Studies content. Staff will be available from 9:00am - 5:00pm on Tuesdays and Wednesdays.

If you need support for ELA, Math, Science, or Social Studies, please call (302) 943-7572.

In addition, if your child attends one of our countywide schools, please call the following hotline number (302) 943-0829.

When calling, please leave both your name, your child’s name and grade, a phone number you can be reached at, and a brief description of what you need support with so we can ensure the right person is able to provide you with the necessary information.

post_text: Though life as we knew it has been transformed into something we are slowly getting to know, CRSD GreenRiders made our district-wide 50th Anniversary of Earth Day a reality in their own unique ways. Here is a small montage of images of some of what CRSD created for this special week. Families headed out to clean up litter in their communities. Kiddos baked Earth cookies and climbed trees to access quiet reading spots. Sidewalks were reimagined with colorful and hopeful artwork and Zoom offices moved outdoors. Green shirts were donned and posters made while virtual celebrations and online activities and lessons were created by our staff. It's a proud, albeit strange, time to be a GreenRider. Thanks to those who shared a few pics and those who celebrated in their own way. The CR Center for Green Schools continues to work toward our unified commitment to sustainable schools in DE especially in this unique time we are in. If you have any questions or suggestions for EcoTeams and our district initiatives, please feel welcomed to reach out the the CRSD Instruction Department.

April 22 at 10:48 PM ·

Huge shout out and thank you to our CRSD Transportation Department!!! They are in the process of delivering books to all our students! A special thank you to Mrs. Cole too for bagging all 700 plus books and our instructional team for putting together our latest book club! 💙💛💙💛💙Being away from school is hard on all of us and we miss our school community! So we decided to do another AFE School Wide Book Club! This book club will feature the book Sideways Stories from Wayside School by Louis Sachar. As we cannot be together, a book will be delivered to you today and tomorrow so that you can read along as we read aloud. Like always, we will have trivia questions and contests. The Book Club will begin April 27th! If you do not receive a book by Friday, please contact us.

For Comcast customers:

Comcast is offering free access to its network for 60 days. Individual households can sign up by using the instructions below. After the 60-day period ends, the cost will be $9.99/month. You can find their announcement here, which provides specific information on this initiative:

https://corporate.comcast.com/press/releases/internet-essentials-low-income-broadband-coronavirus-pandemic

Additionally, Comcast has opened up all their hotspots to anyone that needs them. If one of your students is in range of Comcast hotspot they can go here:

https://wifi.xfinity.com/

post_text: On Friday, Nellie’s Café Jazz Presented The Harlem Renaissance at Nellie H. Stokes Elementary School. The Harlem Renaissance was the development of the Harlem neighborhood in New York City as a black cultural mecca in the early 20th Century and the subsequent social and artistic explosion that resulted. Lasting roughly from the 1910’s through the mid 1930’s, the period is considered a golden age in African American culture, manifesting in literature, music, stage performance and art. #cr #goriders #netde #edude

post_text: On Thursday, Nellie H. Stokes Elementary School held their annual Soul Food Lunch. When the slaves were brought to the America, African cooking styles also came. Different foods were introduced. For example, in Africa, slaves ate a large amount of greens and vegetables and after being brought to America, slaves often served these foods to their masters. African-American food is also called “soul food” and can be found in restaurants and homes not only across America but internationally as well. Some soul foods include fried chicken, sweet potatoes, black eyed peas and cornbread. #cr #goriders #netde #edude

post_text: Yesterday, student interns and staff of the John S. Charlton Roads to Success (R2S) Program at Wesley College presented their card company to the General Federation Women's Clubs-Delaware State Federation Women's Clubs (GFWC DSFWC ) at the Dover Elk Lodge. The Charlton R2S student interns learn valuable entrepreneurial skills through their work with the card company. These include bookkeeping, monitoring inventory, presenting their products, and card development. The Charlton R2S students and staff are grateful for the partnership and the collection of materials by the GFWC DSFWC! #goriders #cr #roadstosuccess

During last night’s Caesar Rodney School District Board of Education meeting they recognized the week the week of February 22nd-29th, 2020 as National FFA Week. Dr. Sherry Kijowski, Principal of Caesar Rodney High School and Donna Urian a freshman at Caesar Rodney High School accepted the recognition.
Future Farmers of America and agricultural education provides a strong foundation for the youth of America and the future of food, fiber, and natural resources systems. The FFA promotes premier leadership, personal growth and career success among its members. Agricultural education and FFA ensure a steady supply of young professionals to meet the growing needs in the science, business, and technology of agriculture. The FFA motto “Learning to Do, Doing to Learn, Earning to Live, Living to Serve” gives direction and purpose to these students who take an active role in succeeding in agriculture education. FFA promotes citizenship, volunteerism, patriotism, and cooperation. #cr #goriders

post_text:
During last night’s Caesar Rodney School District Board of Education meeting they recognized
the week of February 2nd-8th, 2020 as School Counselor Week. F. Niel Postlethwait Middle School Counselor Diane Courtney and Major George S. Welch Elementary School Counselor Heidi Wuller accepted the recognition on behalf of the counselors in the Caesar Rodney School District.
Our school district counselors help our students reach their potential, achieve school success and plan for a career. They are actively committed to helping students explore their abilities, strengths, interests, and talents as these traits relate to career awareness and development. They help parents focus on the way to further the educational, personal and social growth of their children. Our school counselors also work with our teachers to help students explore their potential and set realistic goals for themselves. They seek to identify and utilize community resources that can enhance and complement comprehensive school counseling programs and help students become productive members of society. #cr #goriders

post_text: During last night’s Caesar Rodney School District Board of Education meeting they recognized Terri “Riki” Senn for being selected for the 2020 ProStart National Educator of Excellence Award and James H. Maynard Award. Chef Senn was nominated for this prestigious honor by the Delaware Restaurant Association Educational Foundation for being an “All In” Educator. Chef Senn’s ProStart Program has been recognized as the best in the state of Delaware. This is a direct result of her because of her leadership, encouragement, and motivation. As an educator, Chef Senn is involved, passionate, and caring. Because of her inspiration, our students continue pursuing careers in the culinary arts. #cr #goriders

post_text:
During last night’s Caesar Rodney School District Board of Education meeting they awarded Imperial Nutrition the Spirit of Caesar Rodney Volunteer Award. The owners Imperial Nutrition in Milford, Carlee Merix and Tammy Merix gathered donations from their communities to ensure that every student attending the Kent Elementary ILC had gifts for Christmas. With the high percentage of homeless, displaced, and low-income students attending the KEILC, it was evident that not all of our students would be able to experience opening up Christmas gifts at home. By collaborating with KEILC administration, placing flyers in their nutrition clubs, and requesting donations on their social media channels, the owners of Imperial Nutrition provided the students of Kent Elementary ILC with over $500 worth of new toys and gifts that students received
before leaving for winter break. #cr #goriders

post_text: Today, Nellie H. Stokes Elementary School launched its composting pilot program. EcoTeam students worked together to collect food waste items from their peers during lunch periods in the cafeteria. Using stainless steel collection buckets passed down the lunchroom tables, the EcoTeam diverted quite a bit of food waste from going to our landfill. The food scraps, which only consist of plant-based material, were then transferred to the compost tumbler outdoors. The food waste material will break down into nutrient-rich compost and be added to the soil in their developing Community Gardens. #cr #goriders #ecoteam #greenriders

post_text: All students at Allen Frear Elementary received a copy of the book “Hidden Figures” for Black History Month. “Hidden Figures” explores the story of four female African American mathematicians at NASA, known as "colored computers," and how they overcame gender and racial barriers to succeed in a highly challenging STEM-based career. As a connection activity, Nancy Lee Rodden with ILC Dover came to talk to the students about how the astronaut spacesuit works and why they are so important in protecting the astronauts. #goriders #cr #netde #edude #blackhistorymonth #ILCDover #space #astronauts #spacesuit #hiddenfigures #nasa #stem

post_text:
During yesterday’s in-service day, the teaching staff from Dover Air Base Middle School and Fred Fifer III Middle School participated in The Community Action Poverty Simulation presented by the Delaware State Education Association. In the simulation, teachers spent the day walking in the shoes of families who live in poverty. The experience is designed to help them better understand how the challenges of poverty make their way into the classroom.
The Community Action Poverty Simulation (CAPS) bridges that gap from misconception to understanding. It sensitizes community participants to the realities of poverty. #cr #goriders #netde #edude

post_text: During the teacher in-service day yesterday, the staff at W.B. Simpson Elementary School played The Brain Architecture Game, a game about the powerful role of relationships on early brain development. The Brain Architecture Game is a tabletop game experience that builds an understanding of the powerful role of experiences on early brain development – what promotes it, what derails it, with what consequences for society. The staff also participated in lessons in martial arts, yoga, sound meditation, art therapy, and mindful eating to help in reducing stress. #cr #goriders #netde #edude

Allen Frear Elementary School has committed to improving its’ school climate and increasing student engagement by participating in The Great Kindness Challenge.

post_text:
Today, author Paul Volponi was at Fifer Middle School working with the advance English 7th grade students, providing individual feedback on their writings. On Thursday, Paul will be meeting with the entire 8th grade class in a workshop format to encourage reading and writing in their classes and to further their education. #cr #goriders #netde #edude #paulvolponi

Paul Volponi is writer, teacher and journalist living in New York City. Paul has written 11 novel for young adults that are currently being read in high schools and middle schools around the country. From 1992-1998, he taught incaracerated teens on Rikers Island to read and write. That experience formed the basis of his ALA Award-winning novels Rikers High and Black and White. From 1999-2005, Paul taught teens in drug treatment programs, inspiring his ALA Award-winning novel Rooftop. As a journalist, Paul covers the sport of Thoroughbred racing for the national publication The Blood-Horse.

post_text: Yesterday, members of the Delaware Thunder Professional Hockey Team made a visit to Star Hill Elementary to talk with 4th and 5th graders about being a professional athlete and their career pathways. #goriders #cr #netde #edude #delawarethunder

post_text: Today, the Student Lighthouse Team at W. Reily Brown Elementary School and Rep. Andria Bennett unveiled their Lemonade Stand Law that they have been working on together during a press event at W. Reily Brown Elementary School. The legislation would protect kids’ lemonade stands from regulations and licensing fees. HB 270 will be formally introduced in Thursday’s pre-file legislation. #cr #goriders #netde #edude #lemonadestandlaw
